&s;ymphony, and for &s;ome moments &s;he
remained lo&s;t in the &s;weet &s;en&s;ations
which the mu&s;ic and the &s;cenery had
in&s;pired. She was awakened from her
reverie, by a &s;igh that &s;tole from among
the trees, and directing her eyes whence
it came, beheld&mdash;Hippolitus! A thou|&s;and
<PB N="99" REF="101">
&s;and &s;weet and mingled emotions pre&s;&s;|ed
upon her heart, yet &s;he &s;carcely dar|ed
to tru&s;t the evidence of &s;ight. He
advanced, and throwing him&s;elf at her
